						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="italic">Stone set up in front of the Government farm office.</hi></p>						

						<p>A.D. 993.</p>						

						<p>This fragmentary inscription is dated <hi rend="bold">in Śaka 915, Vijaya, Jyēshṭha śu. 3, Friday.</hi> In the year cited there were two <hi rend="italic">Jyēshṭhas,</hi> and the <hi rend="italic">tithi</hi> śu. 3 fell in those months, on <hi rend="bold">April 27, A.D. 993, Thursday</hi> and <hi rend="bold">May 26, Friday, f.d.t. ·04.</hi> The latter apparently is the intended date.</p>						

						<p>It mentions <hi rend="bold">Śōbhnarasa</hi> as governing <hi rend="bold">Banavāsi-dēśa</hi> and the division of <hi rend="bold">Two Sixhundreds.</hi> This Śōbhanarasa is probably the same as the feudatory of <hi rend="bold">Taila II</hi> and <hi rend="bold">Iṟivabeḍaṅga Satyāśraya</hi> of the <hi rend="bold">Later Chālukya</hi> family of <hi rend="bold">Kalyāṇa</hi> (Cf. <hi rend="italic">Bombay Karnatak Inscriptions,</hi> Vol. I, pt. I, Nos 47 and 50).</p>						

						</summary>
